04470nam a22006855i 9780271062839DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212009pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710628397 a10.1515/97802710628392doi  a(DE-B1597)583918  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aHC59.7b.M369 2009 7aPOL0090002bisacsh04a338.92221 aManzetti, Luigi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aNeoliberalism, Accountability, and Reform Failures in Emerging Markets :bEastern Europe, Russia, Argentina, and Chile in Comparative Perspective /cLuigi Manzetti. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tcontents -- tPreface -- tONE Accountability and Market Reforms -- tTWO Financial Crises in Comparative Perspective -- tTHREE Russia -- tFOUR Argentina -- tFIVE Chile -- tSIX Conclusion -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe agenda of neoliberal market reform known as the Washington Consensus, which was meant to turn around the economies of developing and postcommunist countries and provide the bedrock of economic success on which stable democracies could be built, has largely proved to be a failure, with Russia and many Latin American countries like Argentina left in severe economic crisis by the end of the 1990s. Some proponents of neoliberal reform, such as Anne Krueger, have attributed this failure to the piecemeal and incomplete implementation of reform measures, while others, including Nobel Prize economist and former World Bank vice president Joseph Stiglitz, have pointed to technical flaws in the policies. While both of these assessments focus narrowly on economic factors, Luigi Manzetti highlights the crucial importance of political institutions and processes to a fully adequate explanation. His argument is that the ideology of neoliberal reform, rooted in the theories of Friedrich von Hayek and Milton Friedman, assumed political checks and balances that did not exist in many of these countries undergoing market reform, and that only by taking political accountability as an influential variable in the equation for success can we really understand what happened. Where accountability was weak, patterns of corruption, collusion, and patronage worked to undermine the intended aims of market reform. Manzetti uses both large N statistical analyses and small N case studies (of Argentina, Chile, and Russia) to provide empirical evidence for his argument.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aGovernment accountabilityxDeveloping countries. 0aGovernment accountabilityzDeveloping countries. 0aNeoliberalismxDeveloping countries. 0aNeoliberalismzDeveloping countries. 0aStructural adjustment (Economic policy)xDeveloping countries. 0aStructural adjustment (Economic policy)zDeveloping countries. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Comparative Politics.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271062839423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271062839.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK